WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:19.040
Little Women, by Louisa M. Olcott, retold by Anne Collins.

00:19.040 --> 00:25.320
Chapter 1 The March Sisters

00:25.320 --> 00:31.800
The place was a small town in Massachusetts, North America.

00:31.800 --> 00:37.360
It was a cold evening in December 1862.

00:37.360 --> 00:41.160
Snow was falling softly.

00:41.160 --> 00:48.040
In the living room of a small house, four sisters were sitting by the fire.

00:48.040 --> 00:56.080
Her names were Meg, Joe, Beth, and Amy March.

00:56.080 --> 00:59.160
Meg was 16 years old.

00:59.160 --> 01:02.040
Joe was 15.

01:02.040 --> 01:08.720
Beth was 13 years old, and Amy was 12.

01:08.720 --> 01:13.600
Their mother, Mrs. March, was not in the house.

01:13.600 --> 01:18.360
She was visiting a poor, sick family.

01:18.360 --> 01:23.760
Their father, Mr. March, was far away from home.

01:23.760 --> 01:26.000
It was wartime.

01:26.000 --> 01:31.880
Mr. March was working in a hospital for soldiers.

01:31.880 --> 01:35.720
The four sisters were knitting with wool.

01:35.720 --> 01:39.680
They were knitting socks for the soldiers.

01:39.680 --> 01:42.520
They worked, and they talked.

01:42.520 --> 01:48.160
"'We are poor,' said Meg, the eldest girl.

01:48.160 --> 01:54.040
"'It is terrible,' Meg was very pretty.

01:54.040 --> 01:58.040
She had large eyes and soft brown hair.

01:58.040 --> 02:06.200
"'Other girls have lots of pretty things,' said Amy, the youngest girl.

02:06.200 --> 02:10.120
They had golden hair and blue eyes.

02:10.120 --> 02:16.720
"'I hate girls' work and girls' things,' said Joe.

02:16.720 --> 02:19.520
She was tall and thin.

02:19.520 --> 02:22.360
She had beautiful, long red hair.

02:22.360 --> 02:26.920
"'I don't want to stay at home,' she said.

02:26.920 --> 02:31.720
"'I want to fight in the war.'

02:31.720 --> 02:33.640
Then Beth spoke.

02:34.280 --> 02:37.720
"'Yes, we are poor,' she said.

02:37.720 --> 02:40.280
"'But we are lucky, too.'

02:40.280 --> 02:47.160
"'We have father and mother, and we have each other.'

02:47.160 --> 02:50.200
Beth was very shy.

02:50.200 --> 02:56.920
She was afraid of strangers, but she loved her family very much.

02:56.920 --> 03:01.080
"'Yes, we have each other,' said Joe,

03:01.080 --> 03:07.080
and the girls were happy again.

03:07.080 --> 03:10.760
"'It's six o'clock,' said Meg.

03:10.760 --> 03:13.240
"'Be quick, everybody.

03:13.240 --> 03:15.400
Mother is coming.

03:15.400 --> 03:19.320
We must get supper ready.'

03:19.320 --> 03:22.520
Joe brought more wood for the fire.

03:22.520 --> 03:25.080
Meg lit the lamps.

03:25.080 --> 03:29.720
Beth and Amy put the food on the table.

03:29.800 --> 03:34.760
The door opened and Mrs. March came into the room.

03:34.760 --> 03:41.720
Mrs. March was not beautiful, but she was very kind and good.

03:41.720 --> 03:45.080
Her daughters had a special name for her.

03:45.080 --> 03:48.520
They called her Marmee.

03:48.520 --> 03:53.000
"'How are you, my dears,' said Mrs. March.

03:53.000 --> 03:55.560
"'Did you have a good day?'

03:55.640 --> 04:01.320
"'Yes, thank you, Marme,' replied the four sisters.

04:01.320 --> 04:06.600
"'Come, sit down by the fire, Marme,' said Meg.

04:06.600 --> 04:09.640
"'Suppa is ready.'

04:10.680 --> 04:14.280
"'After supper,' Mrs. March said,

04:14.280 --> 04:19.400
"'Girls, I have a wonderful surprise.'

04:19.480 --> 04:21.960
Everybody was excited.

04:21.960 --> 04:26.120
"'Is it a letter from Father?' asked Joe.

04:26.120 --> 04:29.720
"'Yes,' replied Mrs. March.

04:29.720 --> 04:32.760
"'Father has a Christmas message for all of you.'

04:34.520 --> 04:36.600
The girls read their father's letter.

04:39.640 --> 04:43.000
"'To my four little women,' the letter said,

04:43.880 --> 04:49.160
"'My dears, I will not see you again for a long time.

04:50.440 --> 04:53.080
"'I think of you all every day.

04:54.760 --> 04:56.120
"'Take care of your mother.

04:57.320 --> 04:59.400
"'Be good and work hard.

05:00.920 --> 05:04.280
"'Happy Christmas from your loving father.'"

05:13.880 --> 05:21.560
CHAPTER 2

05:23.320 --> 05:25.000
A WONDERFUL CHRISTMAS

05:27.800 --> 05:30.840
A few days later, it was Christmas Day.

05:32.280 --> 05:35.400
On Christmas morning, the girls woke early.

05:36.440 --> 05:41.000
Each girl had one present, a book from their mother.

05:41.960 --> 05:43.560
They ran downstairs.

05:44.440 --> 05:45.880
They wanted to thank her.

05:47.240 --> 05:49.400
But Mrs. March was not there.

05:51.160 --> 05:54.040
A special Christmas breakfast was on the table.

05:55.320 --> 05:59.240
There was lots of food, and everybody was hungry.

06:00.520 --> 06:02.760
But the girls waited for their mother.

06:04.120 --> 06:05.880
They waited nearly an hour.

06:07.160 --> 06:09.480
At last, their mother came home.

06:11.080 --> 06:14.200
"'Merry Christmas, Marmy,' the girls shouted.

06:15.000 --> 06:18.360
"'Come, sit down. Let's eat breakfast.'"

06:19.400 --> 06:23.400
"'Merry Christmas, little daughters,' said Mrs. March.

06:24.840 --> 06:28.120
"'Listen, I have something to tell you.'

06:29.560 --> 06:32.600
"'There is a poor woman,' Mrs. Hummel.

06:33.480 --> 06:34.680
"'She lives in the town.

06:35.720 --> 06:37.320
"'She has seven children.

06:38.280 --> 06:39.240
"'One is a baby.'

06:40.040 --> 06:44.760
"'The Hummel's house is very cold, and they have no food.

06:46.200 --> 06:48.280
"'Will you give them a Christmas present?

06:49.400 --> 06:51.400
"'Will you give them your breakfast?'"

06:53.480 --> 06:55.720
All the girls were very hungry.

06:56.680 --> 06:58.680
For a moment, nobody spoke.

07:00.040 --> 07:01.080
Then Joe said,

07:02.280 --> 07:06.440
"'Yes, we will, Marmy. Let's take the food to them now.'"

07:07.000 --> 07:10.760
It was early morning, and it was cold.

07:10.760 --> 07:14.360
The girls walked quickly through the snow.

07:14.360 --> 07:18.360
They carried baskets of food and wood for the fire.

07:21.800 --> 07:25.160
The Hummel family lived in one small room.

07:27.160 --> 07:29.400
The room was in a house near a river.

07:30.600 --> 07:34.600
The windows of the room were broken, and there was no fire.

07:34.680 --> 07:36.600
Mrs. Hummel lay in her bed.

07:37.880 --> 07:39.240
She was ill.

07:39.880 --> 07:44.440
The baby was crying, and the children were cold and hungry.

07:46.040 --> 07:50.520
The Hummel children saw the March sisters and the baskets of food.

07:51.720 --> 07:53.560
They shouted happily,

07:53.560 --> 07:57.320
"'Thank you, thank you,' they shouted.

07:58.520 --> 08:02.760
The girls made a fire, and they put the food on the fire.

08:03.320 --> 08:05.160
And they put the food on the table.

08:06.360 --> 08:08.120
Mrs. March made some tea.

08:09.640 --> 08:11.320
Soon the room was warm.

08:12.520 --> 08:16.120
The hungry children ate the food, and they laughed.

08:18.840 --> 08:21.640
Later Mrs. March and her daughters went home.

08:23.000 --> 08:28.120
They had bread and milk for breakfast, but they were very happy.

08:28.120 --> 08:33.080
The March sisters often acted in plays.

08:34.200 --> 08:35.560
Joe wrote the plays.

08:36.840 --> 08:40.600
The girls acted in a small room at the top of the house.

08:41.960 --> 08:46.120
They put on brightly colored clothes, and they enjoyed themselves.

08:48.360 --> 08:51.720
On Christmas evening, the girls acted in a play.

08:52.840 --> 08:54.200
All their friends came.

08:55.560 --> 08:57.480
Everybody enjoyed the play.

08:58.280 --> 09:04.440
Later, their friends went home, and the girls had a lovely surprise.

09:05.640 --> 09:07.320
Mrs. March called to them.

09:08.680 --> 09:10.840
"'Sapper is ready,' she said.

09:12.200 --> 09:14.040
The girls ran downstairs.

09:15.240 --> 09:18.680
They saw lots of delicious food on the table.

09:19.560 --> 09:23.560
Cakes, sweets, fruit, and ice cream.

09:24.440 --> 09:27.560
"'Where did this lovely food come from, Marme?'

09:28.280 --> 09:29.080
Amy asked.

09:30.200 --> 09:31.560
Mrs. March smiled.

09:32.520 --> 09:35.960
"'Old Mr. Lawrence sent it,' she replied.

09:37.400 --> 09:41.080
"'Old Mr. Lawrence, our neighbor,' asked Meg.

09:41.880 --> 09:43.080
She was surprised.

09:44.200 --> 09:46.840
"'But we don't know him,' she said.

09:48.280 --> 09:52.040
"'He heard about your breakfast,' said Mrs. March.

09:52.920 --> 09:55.560
"'He has sent you a special Christmas supper.'

09:57.080 --> 09:58.680
"'The girls looked at each other.

10:00.200 --> 10:07.400
"'This is a wonderful Christmas,' Beth said.

10:07.560 --> 10:13.800
"'The girls looked at each other, and the girls looked at each other.'

10:19.000 --> 10:19.880
Chapter 3.

10:21.640 --> 10:22.120
Lori

10:24.680 --> 10:29.000
Next to the March's small house, there was a large house.

10:30.200 --> 10:33.960
The sisters called this house, the Lawrence house.

10:34.840 --> 10:38.040
"'It belonged to their neighbor, Mr. Lawrence.'

10:39.800 --> 10:43.560
"'Mr. Lawrence was old, and he was very rich.

10:44.760 --> 10:47.000
"'His house was very beautiful.

10:48.360 --> 10:50.760
"'He lived in the house with his grandson.

10:52.360 --> 10:56.840
"'His grandson was fifteen, the same age as Joe.'

10:58.680 --> 11:02.760
"'Sometimes the March sisters saw Mr. Lawrence's grandson.'

11:03.960 --> 11:06.440
"'But the boy was always alone.'

11:11.000 --> 11:14.520
A few days after Christmas, Joe was in her garden.

11:15.800 --> 11:18.520
She was wearing boots and an old coat.

11:19.960 --> 11:21.000
Joe was busy.

11:22.200 --> 11:25.160
She was sweeping snow from the path with a broom.

11:29.080 --> 11:31.080
Joe looked up at the Lawrence house.

11:31.960 --> 11:35.000
She saw a face looking out of a window.

11:36.200 --> 11:38.440
It was Mr. Lawrence's grandson.

11:40.360 --> 11:44.920
"'The boy is sad. He is lonely,' thought Joe.

11:46.600 --> 11:48.040
Then she had an idea.

11:49.400 --> 11:52.440
She took some snow, and she made a ball with it.

11:53.640 --> 11:55.480
She threw the ball at the window.

11:57.000 --> 11:59.800
The boy laughed, and he opened the window.

12:01.080 --> 12:02.840
"'Hello,' called Joe.

12:03.800 --> 12:04.600
"'Are you ill?'

12:05.960 --> 12:08.920
"'I was ill last week,' said the boy.

12:09.800 --> 12:13.000
"'I'm better now, but I'm very bored.

12:13.800 --> 12:15.640
"'I am not doing anything.'

12:16.760 --> 12:19.000
"'I'll visit you,' said Joe.

12:20.040 --> 12:23.160
"'Yes, please come,' said the boy.'

12:25.560 --> 12:29.880
A few minutes later, Joe knocked on the door of the Lawrence house.

12:31.640 --> 12:33.720
She was carrying a small basket.

12:35.000 --> 12:37.960
The basket was full of apples and cakes.

12:39.640 --> 12:41.080
The boy opened the door,

12:43.000 --> 12:44.760
and Joe gave him the basket.

12:46.360 --> 12:48.840
"'These things are for you,' she said.

12:49.640 --> 12:50.920
"'They are from my mother.'

12:52.360 --> 12:55.000
"'Thank you very much,' said the boy.

12:56.120 --> 12:57.000
"'Please come in.'

12:57.800 --> 13:02.680
"'My name is Laurie, and you're Joe, aren't you?'

13:03.800 --> 13:05.480
"'Yes,' said Joe.

13:06.360 --> 13:08.120
"'She was very surprised.'

13:09.320 --> 13:10.840
"'How do you know my name?'

13:12.360 --> 13:15.000
"'I know your name,' said Laurie.

13:15.880 --> 13:18.120
"'I know all your sister's names.'

13:19.240 --> 13:21.480
"'You call to each other in your garden.'

13:21.880 --> 13:26.680
"'Sometimes I see you with your mother,'

13:27.480 --> 13:28.760
Laurie said sadly.

13:29.720 --> 13:31.400
"'I have no mother.

13:32.520 --> 13:33.800
"'My parents are dead,

13:35.000 --> 13:37.320
"'so I live here with my grandfather.

13:38.680 --> 13:41.320
"'But my grandfather is not at home today.'

13:44.040 --> 13:47.800
"'Laurie is rich, but he's very lonely,'

13:48.440 --> 13:49.160
thought Joe.

13:50.440 --> 13:53.800
"'I am poor, but I have a family,

13:54.360 --> 13:56.040
and I have a happy home.'

13:57.880 --> 14:00.200
"'Please visit us,' said Joe.

14:01.080 --> 14:02.120
"'We are neighbors.

14:02.920 --> 14:04.280
"'Let's be friends too.'"

14:07.400 --> 14:10.360
Joe and Laurie talked all afternoon.

14:11.800 --> 14:13.640
Joe talked about her family.

14:14.920 --> 14:16.760
Laurie talked about his life.

14:18.200 --> 14:19.640
He did not go to school.

14:20.600 --> 14:24.520
A teacher, Mr. Brooke, came to the house every day.

14:26.200 --> 14:28.600
Mr. Brooke taught Laurie his lessons.

14:30.200 --> 14:33.000
"'Come into our library,' said Laurie.

14:33.720 --> 14:36.520
"'We have many fine books in the library.'"

14:39.080 --> 14:42.840
The library was a beautiful room with big windows.

14:43.880 --> 14:46.920
There were hundreds of interesting books on the shelves.

14:48.040 --> 14:50.760
There were many fine pictures on the walls.

14:52.360 --> 14:55.560
"'What a wonderful room,' said Joe.

14:57.160 --> 15:00.040
Suddenly, Laurie and Joe heard a noise.

15:01.320 --> 15:04.280
"'Grandfather has come home,' said Laurie.

15:05.160 --> 15:06.280
"'I must go to him.

15:07.080 --> 15:08.280
"'Please stay here.'"

15:10.440 --> 15:12.280
Laurie went out of the library.

15:13.560 --> 15:15.000
Joe stood by the fire.

15:15.960 --> 15:19.560
There was a picture of old Mr. Lawrence on the wall.

15:21.160 --> 15:22.600
Joe looked at the picture.

15:24.200 --> 15:26.120
The door of the library opened,

15:26.680 --> 15:28.440
but she did not turn round.

15:30.600 --> 15:32.040
"'Laurie,' she said,

15:33.080 --> 15:37.240
"'Mr. Lawrence, your grandfather, is not handsome,

15:38.280 --> 15:39.960
but he has a kind face.

15:40.840 --> 15:41.720
I like him.'"

15:43.000 --> 15:45.160
"'Thank you,' said a voice.

15:46.440 --> 15:48.040
Joe turned round quickly.

15:48.840 --> 15:51.320
Mr. Lawrence was standing near the door.

15:52.760 --> 15:54.040
"'Oh,' she said,

15:55.000 --> 15:56.040
"'I'm sorry.'"

15:57.400 --> 16:02.040
"'So, I'm not handsome,' asked Mr. Lawrence.

16:03.400 --> 16:05.240
"'Well, no, sir.'

16:06.040 --> 16:08.760
"'But I have a kind face.'"

16:10.120 --> 16:12.920
"'Yes, you do, sir,' replied Joe.

16:14.120 --> 16:15.560
"'Mr. Lawrence laughed.'"

16:16.600 --> 16:19.560
"'I knew your grandfather,',' he said.

16:20.440 --> 16:21.720
"'He was a good man.'"

16:22.920 --> 16:25.080
"'Now, have some tea.'"

16:27.480 --> 16:29.240
Laurie was very happy.

16:30.360 --> 16:33.240
Laurie and Joe drank tea, and they talked.

16:34.120 --> 16:35.640
Mr. Lawrence watched them.

16:37.000 --> 16:40.040
"'My grandson is happy,' he thought.

16:41.080 --> 16:42.280
He was lonely.

16:43.160 --> 16:44.920
He must have some friends.'"

16:48.920 --> 16:50.600
Later, Joe went home.

16:51.560 --> 16:55.640
She told her mother and her sisters about the Lawrence's beautiful house.

16:56.440 --> 17:00.680
"'Marmy, please let Laurie visit us,' she said.

17:01.720 --> 17:04.360
"'Yes, dear,' replied Mrs. March.

17:05.320 --> 17:08.920
Your new friend Laurie will be welcome in our house.'"

17:08.920 --> 17:25.800
Chapter 4

17:27.080 --> 17:28.920
A Present for Beth

17:31.960 --> 17:35.560
Laurie and the March sisters became good friends.

17:36.680 --> 17:38.360
They visited each other often.

17:39.320 --> 17:41.720
They had many happy days together.

17:43.800 --> 17:46.520
Everybody liked Laurie and his grandfather.

17:47.800 --> 17:51.800
Meg, Joe, and Amy all went to the Lawrence house.

17:53.080 --> 17:55.640
Meg loved flowers and gardens.

17:56.680 --> 17:59.720
She liked the garden at the Lawrence house very much.

18:01.240 --> 18:03.960
It was winter, and there were no flowers.

18:04.840 --> 18:06.680
But there was snow on the trees.

18:07.400 --> 18:08.920
They were very beautiful.

18:11.240 --> 18:15.800
Joe wrote plays and stories, and she loved books.

18:16.920 --> 18:19.480
She liked the library at the Lawrence house.

18:20.840 --> 18:22.680
Amy liked the library, too.

18:24.040 --> 18:25.480
She painted pictures.

18:26.440 --> 18:29.080
She liked the paintings on the library walls.

18:31.160 --> 18:34.040
But Beth did not visit the Lawrence house.

18:35.000 --> 18:36.440
She was very shy.

18:37.240 --> 18:39.560
She was afraid of old Mr. Lawrence.

18:41.960 --> 18:43.640
Beth did not go to school.

18:44.440 --> 18:46.200
She learned her lessons at home.

18:47.800 --> 18:51.560
Beth's life was quiet, but she was very happy.

18:52.840 --> 18:54.840
She helped her mother with the housework.

18:55.640 --> 18:57.560
She learned her lessons every day.

18:59.960 --> 19:01.560
Beth loved music.

19:02.200 --> 19:06.440
The marches had a piano, but it was very old.

19:07.720 --> 19:13.080
Beth tried to play the piano, but the music did not sound very good.

19:14.920 --> 19:18.040
One day Mr. Lawrence spoke to Mrs. March.

19:19.400 --> 19:21.880
Do your daughters play the piano?

19:22.520 --> 19:27.400
He asked, Beth plays the piano, Mrs. March replied.

19:27.480 --> 19:35.400
I have a beautiful piano, said Mr. Lawrence, but nobody plays it now.

19:36.760 --> 19:38.760
Will Beth come to my house?

19:39.800 --> 19:41.320
Will she play the piano?

19:42.840 --> 19:46.120
Beth is very shy, Mrs. March said.

19:47.720 --> 19:52.280
Lori and I are often out of the house, said Mr. Lawrence.

19:53.240 --> 19:54.920
Beth must come then.

19:55.560 --> 19:58.040
We will not hear her playing the piano.

19:59.800 --> 20:02.120
Mrs. March told Beth the news.

20:03.320 --> 20:05.720
Beth was very happy and excited.

20:06.680 --> 20:09.400
She wanted to play Mr. Lawrence's piano.

20:11.800 --> 20:15.080
The next day, Beth went to the Lawrence house.

20:16.440 --> 20:18.440
The house was very quiet.

20:19.880 --> 20:21.480
Good, thought Beth.

20:22.680 --> 20:24.680
Everybody is out of the house.

20:26.360 --> 20:28.200
The piano was in the living room.

20:29.320 --> 20:31.720
Beth walked very quietly into the room.

20:32.840 --> 20:34.200
She touched the piano.

20:35.960 --> 20:38.840
How beautiful it is, she thought.

20:42.600 --> 20:45.880
Some pages of music were lying on top of the piano.

20:47.000 --> 20:48.440
Beth looked at the pages.

20:49.560 --> 20:51.240
The music was not difficult.

20:52.600 --> 20:53.960
So she started to play.

21:00.120 --> 21:02.920
Beth played the piano for many hours.

21:03.640 --> 21:05.720
She enjoyed herself very much.

21:08.280 --> 21:11.320
After that, she went to the Lawrence house every day.

21:12.680 --> 21:15.320
Sometimes, Mr. Lawrence was in the house.

21:16.440 --> 21:21.320
He often listened to the music, but Beth never saw him.

21:22.920 --> 21:31.720
A few weeks past, one day, Beth spoke to her mother.

21:33.480 --> 21:38.200
Marmy, she said, I want to thank Mr. Lawrence.

21:39.240 --> 21:40.920
He has been very kind.

21:42.040 --> 21:43.480
I will give him a present.

21:44.760 --> 21:47.080
Shall I knit a pair of slippers for him?

21:48.360 --> 21:51.080
Yes, Beth, replied Mrs. March.

21:52.040 --> 21:54.120
That's a very good idea.

21:56.280 --> 22:00.760
Beth bought some wool and she made a beautiful pair of slippers.

22:01.800 --> 22:03.640
She took them to the Lawrence house.

22:04.680 --> 22:09.800
Mr. Lawrence was away from home, so Beth wrote a short note.

22:11.160 --> 22:14.040
She put the note and the slippers on a table.

22:15.400 --> 22:16.440
Then she went home.

22:17.160 --> 22:20.360
There was no reply from Mr. Lawrence that day.

22:21.560 --> 22:23.080
Oh, thought Beth.

22:23.720 --> 22:27.160
Mr. Lawrence did not like the slippers.

22:28.360 --> 22:31.160
The next morning, Beth walked by the river.

22:31.800 --> 22:33.240
She was sad.

22:34.200 --> 22:35.720
Later, she went home.

22:36.520 --> 22:38.440
Her sisters were waiting.

22:39.080 --> 22:40.600
They were very excited.

22:41.640 --> 22:44.040
Beth, Beth, come quick.

22:44.120 --> 22:47.800
Beth, Beth, come quickly, they called.

22:48.360 --> 22:50.760
You have a present. Come and see.

22:52.600 --> 22:54.440
They took Beth into the living room.

22:55.560 --> 22:59.480
In the middle of the room was a beautiful little piano.

23:00.600 --> 23:03.560
On top of the piano, there was an envelope.

23:05.560 --> 23:08.280
Open the envelope, Beth, said Joe.

23:09.400 --> 23:12.440
Please open it for me, said Beth.

23:13.240 --> 23:15.160
Joe opened the envelope.

23:15.960 --> 23:17.240
She pulled out a note.

23:18.040 --> 23:20.120
She read it to her mother and sisters.

23:21.400 --> 23:24.280
Dear Miss March, the note said,

23:25.160 --> 23:28.120
I have had many pairs of slippers,

23:29.160 --> 23:31.320
but your slippers are the best.

23:32.760 --> 23:35.160
Thank you for your wonderful present.

23:36.360 --> 23:38.120
Here is a present from me.

23:39.320 --> 23:40.520
Please enjoy it.

23:41.480 --> 23:44.280
Your good friend, James Lawrence.

23:45.880 --> 23:47.720
Beth was very excited.

23:49.000 --> 23:52.200
Mr. Lawrence has given me this piano.

23:52.200 --> 23:54.840
She said, I am very lucky.

23:56.840 --> 23:59.720
Beth sat down at the piano and started to play.

24:01.000 --> 24:03.000
The piano sounded beautiful.

24:04.280 --> 24:06.840
But suddenly, she stopped playing.

24:07.800 --> 24:11.240
I must thank Mr. Lawrence now, she said.

24:12.120 --> 24:14.440
Beth was not shy anymore.

24:15.400 --> 24:19.240
She ran quickly to the Lawrence house and went inside.

24:20.200 --> 24:22.600
Mr. Lawrence was in the library.

24:23.640 --> 24:26.440
Beth ran to him and she kissed him.

24:27.480 --> 24:31.000
Then she said, dear Mr. Lawrence,

24:31.480 --> 24:34.520
thank you so much for my beautiful piano.

24:37.800 --> 24:41.000
Beth was not afraid of Mr. Lawrence anymore.

24:55.640 --> 24:56.520
Chapter 5.

24:58.360 --> 24:59.720
Amy in trouble.

25:02.760 --> 25:04.520
It was Saturday afternoon.

25:05.480 --> 25:07.800
Meg and Joe were in their bedroom.

25:08.760 --> 25:10.440
They were putting on their coats.

25:11.080 --> 25:12.200
They were going out.

25:13.880 --> 25:15.560
Amy came into the bedroom.

25:17.000 --> 25:18.040
Where are you going?

25:18.600 --> 25:19.320
She asked.

25:19.960 --> 25:22.360
Don't ask questions, said Joe.

25:23.240 --> 25:26.520
We're going to the theater with Laurie, said Meg.

25:27.080 --> 25:28.600
We're going to see a play.

25:29.400 --> 25:31.640
Oh, said Amy.

25:32.440 --> 25:33.880
I want to come with you.

25:34.440 --> 25:37.400
Please, no, said Joe.

25:37.880 --> 25:39.320
You are too young.

25:40.200 --> 25:42.520
I'm not too young, she said.

25:43.160 --> 25:44.520
I'm 12 years old.

25:45.400 --> 25:48.040
Please, please let me come with you.

25:50.600 --> 25:53.560
Joe often became angry very quickly.

25:54.360 --> 25:56.680
She became very angry with Amy.

25:57.560 --> 25:59.640
No, Amy, she said.

25:59.640 --> 26:01.560
We will not take you with us.

26:02.120 --> 26:03.240
Please go away.

26:04.840 --> 26:06.280
Amy started to cry.

26:07.240 --> 26:09.880
At that moment, Laurie arrived at the house.

26:10.920 --> 26:14.200
Meg, Joe, are you ready?

26:14.200 --> 26:14.920
He shouted.

26:15.640 --> 26:17.560
We're coming, Joe replied.

26:18.840 --> 26:20.840
Joe and Meg ran downstairs.

26:21.880 --> 26:23.400
Amy stopped crying.

26:24.280 --> 26:27.560
You'll be sorry, Joe March, she shouted.

26:30.040 --> 26:33.000
Joe and Meg had a wonderful time at the theater.

26:33.960 --> 26:35.720
They returned home in the evening.

26:36.920 --> 26:38.360
Amy was reading a book.

26:39.480 --> 26:42.280
She did not ask them questions about the play.

26:44.840 --> 26:49.240
The next day, Meg, Beth, and Amy were sitting in the living room.

26:50.120 --> 26:51.720
They were sitting by the fire.

26:52.680 --> 26:55.160
Suddenly, Joe ran into the room.

26:55.880 --> 26:57.480
She was very upset.

26:58.680 --> 27:00.360
Where is my book of stories?

27:00.920 --> 27:02.120
She asked her sisters.

27:03.080 --> 27:04.040
Have you seen it?

27:05.560 --> 27:07.400
Joe often wrote stories.

27:08.280 --> 27:10.280
She wrote them all in a little book.

27:11.480 --> 27:13.800
But today, she could not find her book.

27:15.160 --> 27:17.880
I haven't seen your book, said Meg.

27:18.760 --> 27:19.960
Have you seen it, Beth?

27:20.920 --> 27:22.600
No, said Beth.

27:24.040 --> 27:25.800
Amy was very quiet.

27:26.440 --> 27:28.440
She did not say anything.

27:29.800 --> 27:32.440
Amy, where is my book of stories?

27:33.000 --> 27:33.640
As Joe.

27:34.760 --> 27:36.840
I don't know, replied Amy.

27:37.800 --> 27:40.200
Yes, you do know, said Joe.

27:40.920 --> 27:43.720
Tell me immediately, where is it?

27:45.080 --> 27:48.120
You'll never see it again, said Amy.

27:49.080 --> 27:51.000
Why not, asked Joe.

27:52.040 --> 27:53.960
I burnt it, said Amy.

27:54.760 --> 27:57.240
You didn't let me come to the theater yesterday,

27:57.880 --> 28:00.760
so I threw your book of stories on the fire.

28:02.280 --> 28:03.960
Joe was very angry.

28:04.920 --> 28:07.560
She held Amy's arms and shouted at her.

28:08.280 --> 28:12.040
You bad, bad girl, Joe shouted.

28:12.680 --> 28:14.920
I wrote those stories for father.

28:15.640 --> 28:17.240
Now they are gone forever.

28:18.920 --> 28:20.760
Suddenly, Amy was sorry.

28:21.400 --> 28:22.600
She started to cry.

28:24.040 --> 28:26.840
Please forgive me, Joe, Amy said.

28:27.720 --> 28:29.640
I'm very, very sorry.

28:30.600 --> 28:32.120
Tears fell from her eyes.

28:32.840 --> 28:35.720
I'll never forgive you, said Joe.

28:36.440 --> 28:36.840
Never.

28:39.480 --> 28:42.040
Joe did not speak to Amy again that day.

28:42.760 --> 28:45.000
She was very angry and upset.

28:48.760 --> 28:51.960
The next day, the weather was very cold.

28:53.000 --> 28:55.080
There was a river near the March's house.

28:56.120 --> 28:57.400
The river had frozen.

28:58.120 --> 28:58.920
It was ice.

29:01.160 --> 29:03.000
Laurie came to the March's house.

29:03.560 --> 29:05.720
He was carrying a pair of ice skates.

29:06.920 --> 29:09.320
Let's go to the river, Joe, he said.

29:09.880 --> 29:11.160
We'll skate on the ice.

29:12.120 --> 29:13.800
All right, replied Joe.

29:14.680 --> 29:17.880
She went to a cupboard and she took out her ice skates.

29:18.920 --> 29:21.560
Amy watched her sister.

29:22.600 --> 29:25.800
After a few minutes, Joe and Laurie left the house.

29:27.800 --> 29:31.000
I want to skate too, Amy said to Meg.

29:32.040 --> 29:35.640
Take your ice skates and run after Joe, said Meg.

29:36.440 --> 29:37.880
Joe will enjoy herself.

29:38.600 --> 29:39.960
She will soon be happy.

29:41.080 --> 29:42.840
Ask her to be your friend again.

29:44.040 --> 29:46.520
That is a good idea, said Amy.

29:49.080 --> 29:51.320
She ran after Joe and Laurie.

29:52.440 --> 29:54.280
The river was not far away.

29:55.720 --> 29:58.920
Soon she saw Joe and Laurie skating on the ice.

30:00.840 --> 30:02.840
Quickly, she put on her ice skates.

30:04.120 --> 30:07.160
The ice was very thin in the middle of the river.

30:08.440 --> 30:10.680
Don't go to the middle of the river, Joe.

30:11.400 --> 30:12.520
Laurie said to Joe.

30:14.040 --> 30:15.880
Joe heard Laurie's words.

30:16.840 --> 30:19.240
But Amy did not hear Laurie.

30:20.200 --> 30:22.120
She skated to the middle of the river.

30:23.800 --> 30:25.960
Suddenly there was a loud crack.

30:27.160 --> 30:28.200
The ice broke.

30:29.560 --> 30:30.840
Amy was in the water.

30:31.880 --> 30:33.240
Help me, Joe.

30:33.240 --> 30:34.040
She shouted.

30:34.840 --> 30:37.160
Laurie skated quickly towards Amy.

30:38.200 --> 30:39.080
Quickly, Joe.

30:39.560 --> 30:41.080
Quickly, he shouted.

30:41.880 --> 30:43.240
We must pull her out.

30:44.120 --> 30:48.520
Joe was terribly afraid, but she followed Laurie.

30:50.360 --> 30:52.600
They pulled Amy from the river.

30:53.560 --> 30:58.200
Amy was not hurt, but she was very cold and frightened.

31:01.000 --> 31:03.320
Joe and Laurie took Amy home.

31:04.040 --> 31:07.160
Mrs. March carried Amy upstairs to her bedroom.

31:08.440 --> 31:10.920
She took off the little girl's wet clothes

31:11.880 --> 31:13.720
and she wrapped her in a blanket.

31:15.480 --> 31:18.280
Then she carried her downstairs to the living room.

31:19.640 --> 31:22.200
Amy fell asleep by the warm fire.

31:24.280 --> 31:26.440
Will Amy be all right, Marme?

31:27.320 --> 31:28.040
Asked Joe.

31:29.000 --> 31:31.480
Yes, dear, replied her mother.

31:32.520 --> 31:36.040
Amy was in trouble, but she will be all right now.

31:36.760 --> 31:37.720
She isn't hurt.

31:38.600 --> 31:40.680
Joe started to cry.

31:42.360 --> 31:45.320
I was angry with Amy, said Joe.

31:46.280 --> 31:48.200
She burnt my book of stories,

31:49.240 --> 31:51.400
but now I am very sorry.

31:52.920 --> 31:55.640
Sometimes I become angry too quickly.

31:56.600 --> 31:58.040
What shall I do, Marme?

31:58.840 --> 31:59.720
Please help me.

32:01.240 --> 32:04.040
Don't cry, Joe, said Mrs. March.

32:05.080 --> 32:06.520
Remember this day.

32:07.480 --> 32:09.320
You won't become angry again.

32:11.240 --> 32:13.720
I will remember, said Joe.

32:15.640 --> 32:19.880
At that moment, Amy opened her eyes and she smiled.

32:21.080 --> 32:23.080
She held out her arms towards Joe.

32:24.440 --> 32:26.360
The two sisters did not speak,

32:27.240 --> 32:30.120
but they kissed and they put their arms around each other.

32:31.240 --> 32:32.440
They were friends again.

32:32.440 --> 32:36.920
Winter soon passed.

32:38.040 --> 32:39.960
Spring came and then summer.

32:40.920 --> 32:43.080
Mrs. March and her daughters were happy,

32:44.280 --> 32:54.280
but they all wanted to see Mr. March again soon.

33:03.320 --> 33:08.040
Chapter six, Meg loses a glove.

33:10.600 --> 33:15.000
Meg, the eldest March sister, was a very pretty girl.

33:15.960 --> 33:18.520
Her friends often invited her to parties.

33:19.880 --> 33:24.280
Meg enjoyed the parties, but sometimes she was sad.

33:25.400 --> 33:28.280
She was sad because her family was poor.

33:29.480 --> 33:31.880
Meg's friends lived in fine houses,

33:32.600 --> 33:38.680
they had beautiful clothes, but Meg did not have beautiful clothes and lovely things.

33:40.920 --> 33:44.600
One day in July, Meg was at a friend's house.

33:45.640 --> 33:47.160
She heard a conversation.

33:48.280 --> 33:52.840
Two women were talking, her friend's mother and another woman.

33:53.800 --> 33:55.640
They were talking about Meg.

33:55.800 --> 34:05.480
Meg March is a kind and lovely girl, said one woman, but her family is poor.

34:06.840 --> 34:11.000
The marches live near the Lawrence's, said the other woman.

34:11.960 --> 34:14.280
The Lawrence's are very rich.

34:15.400 --> 34:19.240
Does Mrs. March have marriage plans for her daughters?

34:20.120 --> 34:23.720
Will one of them marry Mr. Lawrence's grandson?

34:25.640 --> 34:29.240
Meg heard these words, and she was very upset.

34:30.840 --> 34:36.440
I like Laurie very much, she thought, but I do not want to marry him.

34:37.560 --> 34:41.560
We don't think about Laurie's money, he is our best friend.

34:43.480 --> 34:46.200
Meg went home, she spoke to her mother.

34:46.840 --> 34:50.760
Marmy, do you have marriage plans for us?

34:51.160 --> 34:51.960
She asked.

34:52.600 --> 34:55.640
Marriage plans, said Mrs. March.

34:56.600 --> 35:00.040
Meg told her mother all about the women's conversation.

35:01.240 --> 35:03.480
Mrs. March was very angry.

35:04.280 --> 35:07.640
Those women are very foolish, she said.

35:08.360 --> 35:12.280
My daughters are beautiful and good and happy.

35:12.760 --> 35:15.160
They will marry good husbands.

35:17.160 --> 35:21.800
But good men are not always rich men, Mrs. March said.

35:22.920 --> 35:25.560
Love is more important than money.

35:26.920 --> 35:30.360
Don't marry a rich man without love, Meg.

35:31.480 --> 35:34.200
Marry a poor man with love.

35:35.400 --> 35:36.680
Then you will be happy.

35:38.280 --> 35:40.920
You're right, Marmy, Meg said.

35:41.800 --> 35:44.200
I'll always remember your words.

35:47.160 --> 35:50.280
The next day, a letter arrived for Joe.

35:51.720 --> 35:53.800
Joe read the letter to her sisters.

35:56.040 --> 35:58.280
Dear Joe, the letter said,

35:59.400 --> 36:02.760
Tomorrow some new friends will come to visit me.

36:03.880 --> 36:06.280
We will go on a picnic by the river.

36:07.480 --> 36:11.320
I have two boats, we will have a good day.

36:12.760 --> 36:15.560
John Brooke, my teacher, will come with us.

36:16.680 --> 36:21.640
Please come, and please bring Meg, Beth, and Amy too.

36:22.680 --> 36:24.760
Best wishes, Laurie.

36:25.960 --> 36:27.320
A picnic?

36:27.320 --> 36:29.800
That will be exciting, said Amy.

36:30.440 --> 36:33.560
Please, Marmy, we want to go on the picnic.

36:34.520 --> 36:38.440
Very well, go on the picnic, said Mrs. March.

36:39.160 --> 36:40.680
You will have a good time.

36:40.760 --> 36:42.760
The next day was warm and sunny.

36:43.720 --> 36:46.200
Laurie and his new friends walked to the river.

36:47.080 --> 36:49.080
The March girls met them there.

36:49.800 --> 36:52.280
They all brought baskets of food.

36:52.840 --> 36:56.040
They put the baskets into the two small boats.

36:57.240 --> 36:59.800
The March sisters sat in the boats.

37:00.360 --> 37:03.400
Laurie and his friends rode the boats on the river.

37:04.040 --> 37:07.480
Then they got out, and they found a good day.

37:08.280 --> 37:12.040
Then they got out, and they found a good place for the picnic.

37:13.320 --> 37:16.680
Everybody was hungry, and the food was delicious.

37:18.920 --> 37:24.200
Later, Joe, Laurie, Beth, and Amy talked to Laurie's friends,

37:24.760 --> 37:26.040
and they played games.

37:28.280 --> 37:30.200
Meg was reading a German book.

37:31.080 --> 37:33.480
She did not understand some of the words.

37:34.760 --> 37:37.000
Mr. Brooke, Laurie's teacher,

37:37.640 --> 37:38.760
understood German.

37:39.560 --> 37:41.320
He helped Meg with the words.

37:43.400 --> 37:45.640
Mr. Brooke was a quiet young man.

37:46.600 --> 37:49.320
He had brown eyes and a kind face.

37:50.440 --> 37:55.080
He often looked at Meg, but Meg did not see him looking at her.

37:56.600 --> 38:00.200
You're a very good teacher, Mr. Brooke, said Meg.

38:01.240 --> 38:03.560
Thank you, replied Mr. Brooke.

38:04.440 --> 38:05.640
I enjoy my work.

38:06.520 --> 38:08.440
Laurie is a very good student.

38:10.760 --> 38:13.080
Everybody had a good time at the picnic.

38:14.200 --> 38:16.120
At last, they had to go home.

38:20.840 --> 38:23.800
The next day, Meg was looking for her gloves.

38:26.120 --> 38:28.360
I've lost a glove, she said.

38:29.000 --> 38:30.200
Have you seen it, Joe?

38:31.160 --> 38:33.880
No, I haven't seen it, replied Joe.

38:34.600 --> 38:36.040
Did you lose it at the picnic?

38:36.680 --> 38:37.800
I'll ask Laurie.

38:39.560 --> 38:43.800
Later, Joe said to Laurie, Meg has lost a glove.

38:44.920 --> 38:46.360
Laurie started to laugh.

38:47.240 --> 38:49.960
I know where her glove is, he said.

38:50.920 --> 38:53.080
Where is it, asked Joe?

38:54.200 --> 38:58.360
I will tell you, said Laurie, but don't tell Meg.

38:59.480 --> 39:02.040
I won't tell Meg, said Joe.

39:03.000 --> 39:07.800
The glove is in John Brooke's pocket, said Laurie.

39:09.240 --> 39:10.840
Joe did not understand.

39:11.800 --> 39:13.720
What do you mean, she said?

39:14.600 --> 39:17.240
Why is the glove in John Brooke's pocket?

39:18.440 --> 39:21.800
Meg dropped her glove, and John Brooke found it.

39:22.360 --> 39:25.880
Said Laurie, he put the glove in his pocket.

39:26.600 --> 39:28.200
He looks at it every day.

39:29.240 --> 39:30.920
John is in love with Meg.

39:31.720 --> 39:33.000
Isn't that wonderful?

39:34.280 --> 39:36.520
But Joe was angry and upset.

39:37.720 --> 39:39.080
No, she said.

39:39.720 --> 39:43.000
It isn't wonderful, it's terrible news.

39:43.800 --> 39:47.800
Mr. Brooke will marry Meg, he will take her away from us.

39:48.840 --> 39:53.400
No, I am not happy, I am very unhappy.

40:00.920 --> 40:05.160
The

40:11.240 --> 40:14.200
Chapter 7, a telegram.

40:16.680 --> 40:22.840
Summer and autumn passed, it was November, the weather was cold and wet.

40:25.080 --> 40:29.000
One afternoon, the March sisters were sitting in their living room.

40:29.960 --> 40:33.480
Meg looked out of the window, she watched the rain.

40:35.000 --> 40:38.280
November is a terrible month, she said.

40:39.160 --> 40:43.160
It is cold and wet, nothing ever happens.

40:44.040 --> 40:48.040
Our lives are very boring, and we have no money.

40:49.480 --> 40:51.240
Amy was painting a picture.

40:52.760 --> 40:56.280
One day, I'll be a famous artist, she said.

40:57.160 --> 41:01.400
I'll travel to Italy, I'll paint beautiful pictures.

41:02.440 --> 41:06.680
Then I'll sell the pictures, and we will have lots of money.

41:08.040 --> 41:10.920
I'm going to write books, said Joe.

41:11.640 --> 41:15.640
I'll be rich and famous too, that is my dream.

41:16.680 --> 41:18.040
What is your dream, Beth?

41:19.800 --> 41:22.520
I'm very happy now, said Beth.

41:23.400 --> 41:25.880
I shall stay at home with Marmy and Father.

41:27.720 --> 41:31.480
Meg looked out of the window again, suddenly she said,

41:32.360 --> 41:35.240
there's Laurie, he's coming to the front door.

41:37.720 --> 41:40.680
A few moments later, Laurie came into the room.

41:41.560 --> 41:46.600
He was holding a small envelope in his hand, he was worried and upset.

41:47.480 --> 41:51.800
What is it Laurie, said Joe, is something wrong?

41:53.000 --> 41:55.480
Where is Mrs. March, said Laurie?

41:56.280 --> 41:57.960
I have come from the post office.

41:59.480 --> 42:03.960
Laurie held up the envelope, this is a telegram for your mother.

42:04.840 --> 42:07.000
It's from Washington, he said.

42:08.600 --> 42:11.400
At that moment, Mrs. March came into the room.

42:12.840 --> 42:14.360
Laurie gave her the telegram.

42:15.160 --> 42:18.680
Mrs. March opened it, and she read it quickly.

42:19.880 --> 42:23.800
Then she sat down in a chair, her face was white.

42:25.800 --> 42:28.600
The telegram was from a hospital in Washington.

42:30.200 --> 42:33.960
Your husband is very ill, the telegram said.

42:35.000 --> 42:38.440
He is in this hospital, come immediately.

42:39.320 --> 42:43.320
P. Dale, the army hospital, Washington.

42:45.240 --> 42:50.120
I must go to Washington, said Mrs. March.

42:51.080 --> 42:53.320
I will go on the train tomorrow morning.

42:54.360 --> 42:59.560
Joe, run to the post office, send a telegram to the hospital,

43:00.360 --> 43:04.200
send this reply, I will come immediately.

43:05.560 --> 43:11.640
Meg, Beth, Amy, come and help me, I have to pack my case.

43:14.360 --> 43:18.120
The three girls started to help their mother.

43:19.080 --> 43:23.240
Joe put on her hat and she went out, Laurie went home.

43:26.120 --> 43:28.760
Mrs. March went to her desk in the living room.

43:29.640 --> 43:33.320
She opened a drawer, there was some money in the drawer.

43:34.440 --> 43:38.200
She looked at the money, there was not very much.

43:39.800 --> 43:42.840
I have to buy a train ticket, she thought.

43:43.800 --> 43:46.280
Will the girls have enough money for food?

43:48.520 --> 43:51.560
A few minutes later, there was a knock on the front door.

43:53.720 --> 43:55.000
Meg opened the door.

43:56.040 --> 44:01.400
Old Mr. Lawrence and Mr. Brooke, Laurie's teacher, were standing outside.

44:03.800 --> 44:07.080
Laurie told us the bad news about your father.

44:07.720 --> 44:11.000
Said Mr. Lawrence, I'm very sorry.

44:11.960 --> 44:13.880
Will your mother go to Washington?

44:15.000 --> 44:19.640
Yes, said Meg, she will go to Washington tomorrow morning.

44:21.160 --> 44:24.520
She must not go alone, said Mr. Lawrence.

44:25.240 --> 44:26.920
A friend must go with her.

44:28.360 --> 44:33.640
I'm an old man, I am not strong, I can't go with her.

44:34.760 --> 44:40.040
But John Brooke is a young man, he can go to Washington with your mother.

44:41.880 --> 44:47.400
Mr. Brooke looked at Meg and he smiled, his face was very kind.

44:48.520 --> 44:52.840
Don't worry about your mother, he said, I'll take care of her.

44:54.120 --> 44:59.960
Meg was very pleased, thank you very, very much, she said.

45:02.040 --> 45:09.880
Soon everything was ready for Mrs. March's journey, evening came, but Joe had not returned.

45:11.000 --> 45:12.360
Mrs. March was worried.

45:13.800 --> 45:17.800
Where is Joe, she said, it's very late.

45:19.560 --> 45:26.520
At last, Joe came home, she walked into the kitchen and she put some money on the table.

45:27.880 --> 45:31.400
This money is for your journey, Marmy, she said.

45:33.160 --> 45:39.720
Mrs. March looked at the money, then she looked at Joe, she was very surprised.

45:40.600 --> 45:47.320
Twenty-five dollars, she said, Joe, where did you get this money?

45:49.000 --> 45:52.360
Joe did not answer, she took off her hat.

45:53.560 --> 45:58.200
Everybody looked at her, Joe's hair was very short.

45:59.400 --> 46:03.880
Your hair, your beautiful red hair, said Meg.

46:04.840 --> 46:07.240
Oh, Joe, what have you done?

46:10.360 --> 46:13.640
Many women want long red hair, said Joe.

46:14.280 --> 46:20.280
I went to the barber's shop, the barber cut my hair, then I sold him my hair.

46:21.160 --> 46:26.040
He gave me twenty-five dollars for it, I wanted to help Marmy and father.

46:26.200 --> 46:34.920
Tears fell from Mrs. March's eyes, Joe, you are good and kind, she said.

46:36.760 --> 46:40.760
That night, Meg and Joe could not sleep.

46:41.400 --> 46:47.560
Joe was thinking about her hair, Meg was thinking about Mr. Brooke.

46:48.520 --> 46:51.320
Both girls were worrying about their father.

46:56.120 --> 47:00.200
The next morning, Mr. Lawrence's carriage came to the March's house.

47:01.160 --> 47:03.480
Mr. Brooke was sitting inside the carriage.

47:04.840 --> 47:10.840
Mrs. March kissed her daughters and she said goodbye, then she got into the carriage.

47:12.760 --> 47:16.360
The sun shone on the sad faces of the March sisters.

47:17.240 --> 47:22.120
Goodbye, dear Marmy, they said. Goodbye.

47:22.120 --> 47:24.120
Bye.

47:42.680 --> 47:46.200
Chapter eight, Beth is ill.

47:46.200 --> 47:50.680
Mrs. March was in Washington.

47:51.800 --> 47:57.160
The four sisters worked very hard. They did the housework every day.

47:58.440 --> 48:04.440
They were worried about their father and mother, but the girls were very kind to each other,

48:05.400 --> 48:07.640
and they wrote to their mother every day.

48:10.120 --> 48:12.680
Soon a letter arrived from Mrs. March.

48:13.400 --> 48:20.040
My dear daughters, the letter said, I have some wonderful news.

48:21.000 --> 48:25.480
Father is getting better, but he is not strong.

48:26.040 --> 48:29.320
He has to stay in hospital for some weeks.

48:30.040 --> 48:32.760
Then Mr. Brooke and I will bring him home.

48:33.720 --> 48:38.200
Don't worry, little daughters. Take care of each other.

48:39.160 --> 48:41.720
Soon we will all be together again.

48:43.560 --> 48:45.400
Your loving Marmy.

48:47.720 --> 48:54.600
The girls were happy, and soon Meg, Joe, and Amy forgot about the housework.

48:56.040 --> 49:02.440
Beth did not forget. She did her own work, and she did her sister's work too.

49:05.800 --> 49:09.640
One afternoon, Beth, Meg, and Joe were talking.

49:10.360 --> 49:12.200
Amy was not at home.

49:13.720 --> 49:18.680
Meg said Beth, please, will you visit the Hummel family?

49:19.560 --> 49:26.280
Marmy often visits them. Marmy is not here. We must visit the Hummel's.

49:27.320 --> 49:31.800
I'm sorry, Beth. I'm very tired today, said Meg.

49:32.600 --> 49:34.680
Joe must go to the Hummel's house.

49:35.640 --> 49:39.720
I can't go, said Joe. I'm going to meet Laurie.

49:40.600 --> 49:44.920
I can't visit the Hummel's today. You must go yourself, Beth.

49:46.600 --> 49:50.680
I visited the Hummel's every day this week, said Beth.

49:51.640 --> 49:54.760
The baby is ill, and I'm very worried.

49:56.040 --> 50:02.680
Oh, said Meg. Amy will come home soon. Then she must visit the Hummel's.

50:05.160 --> 50:08.760
An hour passed, but Amy did not come home.

50:10.360 --> 50:14.840
Meg and Joe went upstairs. Meg looked at a new dress.

50:16.040 --> 50:22.360
Joe wrote a story. They forgot about the Hummel's. Beth waited.

50:23.480 --> 50:29.160
At last, she put on her coat. She put some food in a basket, and she went out.

50:30.520 --> 50:32.600
Meg and Joe did not see her leaving.

50:35.160 --> 50:39.640
Later, Beth returned. She did not speak to anybody.

50:40.680 --> 50:44.200
She went upstairs to her mother's bedroom, and she shut the door.

50:46.200 --> 50:51.960
An hour later, Joe found Beth. Beth was sitting on her mother's bed.

50:52.920 --> 50:59.080
Her face was white, and she was crying. She was holding a bottle of medicine.

51:00.040 --> 51:02.520
What is wrong, Joe asked?

51:03.400 --> 51:07.400
Oh, Joe, the baby is dead, said Beth.

51:08.120 --> 51:10.360
Which baby asked Joe?

51:11.640 --> 51:13.960
The Hummel baby replied Beth.

51:14.920 --> 51:19.960
I went to the Hummel's house this afternoon. The baby was very ill.

51:20.760 --> 51:27.080
Mrs. Hummel went to get the doctor. I held the baby in my arms, but it died.

51:28.040 --> 51:33.560
Oh, Beth, that is terrible, said Joe. What happened next?

51:34.920 --> 51:38.200
Mrs. Hummel came back with the doctor, said Beth.

51:39.000 --> 51:44.840
The doctor looked at the baby. He said, this baby had scarlet fever.

51:45.640 --> 51:47.960
scarlet fever, said Joe.

51:48.920 --> 51:53.320
Yes, Beth said. The doctor gave me this medicine.

51:54.280 --> 51:57.960
He said, go home immediately, drink some of this.

51:59.080 --> 52:02.280
And now I have a headache, and I'm very hot.

52:03.640 --> 52:09.160
Suddenly Joe was afraid. Has Beth got scarlet fever? She thought.

52:09.880 --> 52:11.960
It is a very dangerous illness.

52:15.160 --> 52:20.760
Don't worry, Beth, Joe said. I'll tell Meg, we will get Marme's doctor.

52:21.240 --> 52:28.280
Meg was very worried. Beth went to the Hummel's house every day, she said, to Joe.

52:29.240 --> 52:32.200
We must get Dr. Bang's immediately.

52:33.160 --> 52:37.000
Dr. Bang's came, and he looked at Beth.

52:37.880 --> 52:40.520
Then the doctor spoke to Meg and Joe.

52:41.560 --> 52:44.440
Beth has scarlet fever, he said.

52:45.240 --> 52:46.840
Who will take care of her?

52:47.320 --> 52:49.240
We will, said Meg.

52:49.320 --> 52:54.200
Said Meg. Joe and I have had scarlet fever. We are safe.

52:55.320 --> 52:57.320
Has Amy had scarlet fever?

52:58.200 --> 52:59.320
Asked Dr. Bang's.

53:00.520 --> 53:05.720
Amy hasn't had the fever, replied Meg. She will not be safe here.

53:06.680 --> 53:09.720
She must stay with father's aunt, Aunt March.

53:10.520 --> 53:12.440
Good, said Dr. Bang's.

53:13.400 --> 53:16.440
Take care of Beth. I'll come again tomorrow.

53:16.440 --> 53:20.040
The doctor left the house.

53:20.920 --> 53:22.200
Joe spoke to Meg.

53:23.240 --> 53:27.960
We must write to Marme, she said. We must tell her about Beth.

53:29.000 --> 53:35.400
No, said Meg. Marme is taking care of father. She can't come home now.

53:36.520 --> 53:41.320
Marme must stay in Washington. We must not tell her about Beth.

53:41.800 --> 53:43.960
Joe started to cry.

53:44.360 --> 53:48.120
Washington is many miles away, she said.

53:48.440 --> 53:52.680
We were wrong, Meg. We didn't visit the Hummels.

53:53.240 --> 53:58.120
Beth went there every day. And now she has scarlet fever.

53:59.080 --> 54:01.880
Oh, Meg, what are we going to do?

54:02.920 --> 54:05.480
Meg put her arms around Joe.

54:06.040 --> 54:08.680
Don't cry, Joe, she said.

54:08.920 --> 54:14.280
She said, Beth has scarlet fever, but she will get better soon.

54:15.320 --> 54:17.000
Now we must take care of her.

54:19.560 --> 54:26.360
The next day, Amy went to Aunt March's house. Megan Joe took care of Beth.

54:39.560 --> 54:48.600
Chapter 9. News from Washington

54:51.560 --> 54:56.680
Beth was very ill. The days passed and she did not get better.

54:58.040 --> 55:06.120
Beth could not eat. She slept for many hours. Sometimes she was awake, but she could not

55:06.120 --> 55:14.200
remember things. Sometimes she called Joe, Meg. Sometimes she called Meg, Joe.

55:15.800 --> 55:22.200
Beth said her mother's name again and again. Joe and Meg were worried and afraid.

55:23.960 --> 55:26.520
One morning, the two girls were talking.

55:27.480 --> 55:36.360
Let's send a telegram to Marmee, said Joe. Let's tell her about Beth now. Then she will come home.

55:37.240 --> 55:43.960
All right, said Meg. She sat down and she wrote the words for a telegram.

55:45.000 --> 55:55.560
Dearest Marmee, she wrote, Beth has scarlet fever. She is very ill. Please come home immediately.

55:56.600 --> 55:59.480
Your loving daughters, Meg and Joe.

56:01.720 --> 56:05.640
I'll take this to the post office this afternoon, said Meg.

56:07.320 --> 56:14.040
But that afternoon, a letter arrived from Mrs. March. There was bad news in the letter.

56:15.000 --> 56:17.240
Mr. March was very ill again.

56:17.960 --> 56:21.960
Meg and Joe read the letter. They looked at each other.

56:23.000 --> 56:32.120
We must not send the telegram to Marmee, said Meg. Beth is ill, but father is ill too.

56:32.600 --> 56:37.320
Marmee must stay with him. She can't come home now.

56:39.320 --> 56:45.080
A week later, it was the first day of December. The weather was very cold.

56:45.560 --> 56:54.520
The wind blew all day and snow fell. In the morning, Dr. Bang's visited the house.

56:55.800 --> 57:01.000
He looked at Beth for a long time. Then he spoke to Meg and Joe.

57:02.680 --> 57:12.360
Beth is very, very ill. He said, your mother must come home immediately. I will come back tonight.

57:13.240 --> 57:17.880
Meg said, Joe, we must send the telegram to Marmee.

57:19.000 --> 57:22.680
Joe put on her coat and hat and she ran outside.

57:23.800 --> 57:28.520
Laurie was walking towards the house. He was holding a letter in his hand.

57:29.480 --> 57:31.640
He was very happy and excited.

57:32.680 --> 57:37.480
I have good news, he said. This letter is from John Brooke.

57:38.280 --> 57:40.120
Your father is getting better now.

57:41.080 --> 57:44.600
But what's wrong, Joe? Where are you going?

57:45.960 --> 57:49.560
I'm going to send a telegram to Marmee, replied Joe.

57:50.600 --> 57:57.240
Dr. Bang's visited Beth. She is very, very ill. Joe started to cry.

57:59.240 --> 58:00.840
Laurie held Joe's hand.

58:02.040 --> 58:08.840
Dear Joe, he said, grandfather and I will always help you. Please remember that.

58:10.200 --> 58:15.640
Yes, said Joe. You are our good friends. Thank you very much.

58:18.600 --> 58:25.880
I must tell you something, said Laurie. Last week, grandfather and I were talking about Beth.

58:26.920 --> 58:34.440
We were very worried about her. We sent a telegram to your mother. We told her about Beth's illness.

58:35.240 --> 58:42.200
Today, I received this letter from John Brooke. Your mother will be here early tomorrow morning.

58:43.080 --> 58:44.920
Then everything will be all right.

58:46.280 --> 58:49.560
Joe was happy again. She stopped crying.

58:50.680 --> 58:55.720
Laurie, she said, you're a wonderful friend. Thank you.

58:56.520 --> 59:04.120
Joe ran inside the house. She told Meg the good news. Meg was very happy, too.

59:06.120 --> 59:13.320
The afternoon passed slowly. Beth lay in her bed. Her eyes were closed.

59:14.120 --> 59:19.880
She did not eat or speak. Sometimes she drank some water.

59:20.280 --> 59:29.240
Meg and Joe sat by her bed. The wind blew and the snow fell. At last, night came.

59:29.800 --> 59:37.480
Meg and Joe watched Beth. They waited for Mrs. March, and they waited for Dr. Bangs.

59:39.480 --> 59:47.640
Old Mr. Lawrence and Laurie waited, too. They sat downstairs in the living room. They sat by the fire.

59:48.200 --> 59:57.240
The hours passed. At two o'clock in the morning, Joe went to the window. She looked out at the garden.

59:58.440 --> 01:00:00.840
There was thick snow everywhere.

01:00:02.040 --> 01:00:10.840
The world is sad and lonely tonight, she thought. Suddenly, she heard a noise. She turned round.

01:00:10.840 --> 01:00:21.800
Meg was crying. Beth has died, thought Joe. Beth has died, and Meg cannot tell me.

01:00:23.400 --> 01:00:29.720
She went to the bed and looked down at Beth. Beth was quiet. Her eyes were closed.

01:00:31.720 --> 01:00:35.240
Then the door opened and Dr. Bangs came into the room.

01:00:36.120 --> 01:00:47.000
Beth is dead, Joe said quietly. Dr. Bangs looked at Beth. He held her hands. Then he smiled.

01:00:47.640 --> 01:00:58.280
No, he said. Beth isn't dead. She's sleeping. She's going to be all right. There is no more danger.

01:00:59.160 --> 01:01:06.440
Meg and Joe put their arms around each other and they cried. They were very, very happy.

01:01:09.240 --> 01:01:14.680
Soon it was morning. The sisters heard the sound of a carriage in the street.

01:01:18.280 --> 01:01:24.600
Then Laurie called from the living room, girls, girls, your mother is here.

01:01:25.400 --> 01:01:27.400
Mrs. March had come home.

01:01:43.400 --> 01:01:48.040
Chapter 10. The Best Christmas Present.

01:01:48.600 --> 01:01:55.320
Amy was unhappy at Aunt March's house. She wanted to see her family.

01:01:55.320 --> 01:02:04.280
Aunt March was an old lady. She did not like young girls. Sometimes she was angry with Amy.

01:02:04.280 --> 01:02:14.760
Every evening, Amy had to read to Aunt March, but she did not like Aunt March's books. They were not very interesting.

01:02:15.640 --> 01:02:18.840
One evening, Aunt March spoke to Amy.

01:02:18.840 --> 01:02:27.880
I have had a letter from your mother, she said. She has come home. She will take you home tomorrow.

01:02:29.160 --> 01:02:31.560
Amy was very happy.

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:39.000
Soon the four sisters were together again and every day Beth was stronger.

01:02:39.080 --> 01:02:50.120
One day a letter came from Washington. It was from John Brooke. Mrs. March read the letter.

01:02:51.400 --> 01:03:00.120
Girls, girls, I have wonderful news, she said. Mr. Brooke is going to bring father home.

01:03:00.120 --> 01:03:09.160
It was a week before Christmas. The March sisters were very busy and excited.

01:03:09.160 --> 01:03:15.640
They made Christmas presents, and they cooked delicious food for Christmas day.

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:20.440
In the evening, Joe spoke to her mother.

01:03:21.320 --> 01:03:28.760
Marmy, she said, I must tell you something. John Brooke loves Meg.

01:03:29.880 --> 01:03:36.520
In the summer, Meg lost a glove. John Brooke found it, and he put it in his pocket.

01:03:37.560 --> 01:03:39.400
Isn't that terrible, Marmy?

01:03:41.000 --> 01:03:44.040
Why is it terrible? asked Mrs. March.

01:03:44.840 --> 01:03:50.680
John Brooke will marry Meg, replied Joe. He'll take her away from us.

01:03:52.120 --> 01:04:01.000
Listen, Joe, said Mrs. March. John Brooke is a good young man. He was very kind and helpful in

01:04:01.000 --> 01:04:09.880
Washington. John Brooke must not marry Meg, Joe said. Meg must not marry a poor man.

01:04:10.520 --> 01:04:19.800
Money is not important, replied Mrs. March. John is good and kind. He loves Meg very much.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:27.000
But Meg is young. She is only 17. They must wait.

01:04:28.440 --> 01:04:32.200
Please don't be sad, Joe, Mrs. March said.

01:04:32.520 --> 01:04:40.280
One day you will leave this house, too. You will meet a good man and you will marry him.

01:04:41.400 --> 01:04:47.640
No, mother, cried Joe. I'll never marry anybody. I want to be a famous writer.

01:04:50.920 --> 01:04:58.120
At last it was Christmas day. Everybody had some presents. Everybody was happy.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:06.440
In the afternoon, Lori and old Mr. Lawrence came to the March's house. They brought presents.

01:05:07.320 --> 01:05:13.560
Everybody talked and everybody laughed. Then somebody knocked at the front door.

01:05:16.440 --> 01:05:23.720
Lori went to the door. A moment later he came back into the living room. He was very excited.

01:05:24.680 --> 01:05:29.080
Here is another Christmas present for the March family, he said.

01:05:30.360 --> 01:05:35.720
A tall man was standing behind Lori. Everybody looked at the man.

01:05:36.680 --> 01:05:43.160
For a moment they did not speak. Then the girls shouted together, father.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:51.640
All the sisters ran to their father. They put their arms around him.

01:05:52.520 --> 01:05:54.920
Everybody was talking and crying.

01:05:55.960 --> 01:05:59.320
This is the best Christmas present, said Amy.

01:06:00.920 --> 01:06:07.400
Then another man came into the room. It was John Brooke. Meg ran towards him.

01:06:08.520 --> 01:06:11.960
I'm very happy to see you, John, she said.

01:06:12.680 --> 01:06:16.040
Thank you. You have brought father home to us.

01:06:16.200 --> 01:06:24.200
Later everybody ate Christmas dinner. Then the Lawrence's and John Brooke went home.

01:06:25.080 --> 01:06:32.120
The March family sat by the fire. Mr. March looked at the faces of his four happy daughters.

01:06:33.320 --> 01:06:41.800
My dears, he said. This year has been very long and difficult. You had to work very hard.

01:06:42.760 --> 01:06:57.720
I left home and you were girls. Now you have grown up. You are four fine women.

01:06:58.680 --> 01:07:00.680
You

01:07:05.080 --> 01:07:08.440
Chapter 11 A Happy Ending

01:07:10.440 --> 01:07:16.920
The marches were together again. Every day Mr. March and Beth were stronger.

01:07:18.520 --> 01:07:25.240
Lori and old Mr. Lawrence often visited the marches, but John Brooke did not come with them.

01:07:26.200 --> 01:07:30.280
Meg was sad. She wanted to see John very much.

01:07:31.960 --> 01:07:37.080
I don't understand, she thought. Why doesn't John visit us?

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:45.560
One afternoon Meg and Joe were talking. Joe saw an umbrella by the front door.

01:07:46.520 --> 01:07:52.120
Who's umbrella is that? She asked. I've never seen it before.

01:07:53.480 --> 01:08:01.720
It's John Brooke's umbrella, replied Meg. He left it here on Christmas Day. He has forgotten it.

01:08:03.400 --> 01:08:09.720
Meg said Joe. Do you like John Brooke? Do you love him?

01:08:10.600 --> 01:08:12.600
Are you going to marry him?

01:08:13.800 --> 01:08:22.680
No, no, Meg said. I'm too young for marriage. Please don't ask me these questions, Joe.

01:08:23.720 --> 01:08:30.520
Then you don't love him, said Joe. Oh, I don't know, said Meg.

01:08:31.760 --> 01:08:33.760
Joe looked out of the window.

01:08:34.320 --> 01:08:39.840
Meg, John Brooke is outside now, she said. He is coming to the front door.

01:08:40.640 --> 01:08:45.040
You don't love him, Meg. He must go away. Please tell him.

01:08:46.480 --> 01:08:52.320
Meg ran to the stairs. She wanted to hide in her bedroom, but it was too late.

01:08:53.440 --> 01:08:55.120
John Brooke came into the house.

01:08:56.480 --> 01:09:02.640
Good afternoon, John said. Do you have my umbrella? I left it here.

01:09:03.440 --> 01:09:07.440
He smiled. Then he said, how is your father?

01:09:08.560 --> 01:09:12.480
He's very well, thank you, said Joe. We'll bring him.

01:09:14.320 --> 01:09:19.520
Joe went upstairs and Meg started to follow, but John Brooke stopped her.

01:09:20.720 --> 01:09:25.920
Please don't go, Meg. He said, I must say something to you.

01:09:26.720 --> 01:09:31.360
Oh, said Meg. Let's talk in the living room.

01:09:32.560 --> 01:09:41.040
John and Meg went into the living room. Meg sat down, and John Brooke sat beside her. He held her hand.

01:09:44.000 --> 01:09:54.320
Dearest Meg, he said, I love you. I am poor, but I can work hard. I can make a good home for you.

01:09:55.120 --> 01:09:58.480
Please, Meg. Will you be my wife?

01:10:00.400 --> 01:10:07.040
At first Meg did not speak. Then she said, I don't know, John.

01:10:08.160 --> 01:10:12.160
Please, Meg, said John Brooke. Will you marry me?

01:10:13.920 --> 01:10:17.680
Suddenly the door opened and Aunt March came into the room.

01:10:18.720 --> 01:10:23.520
Meg and John were very surprised. Aunt March was surprised too.

01:10:24.800 --> 01:10:28.960
Good afternoon, Meg. She said, where is your father?

01:10:29.920 --> 01:10:33.920
Then she looked at John Brooke. Who is this young man?

01:10:35.280 --> 01:10:41.360
Aunt March, this is John Brooke, Meg said. John is father's friend.

01:10:42.480 --> 01:10:49.680
John Brooke? Said Aunt March. Why are you here, young man? What are you talking about?

01:10:50.560 --> 01:10:56.560
Aunt March, said Meg quietly. John Brooke wants to marry me.

01:10:58.320 --> 01:11:06.960
Aunt March looked angrily at John Brooke. Then she said, young man, Mrs. March has spoken about you.

01:11:07.680 --> 01:11:13.120
You are poor. You have no money. Meg must marry a man with money.

01:11:14.560 --> 01:11:18.720
Meg was very angry. And March, she said.

01:11:19.680 --> 01:11:24.160
John is poor, but he is a good man, and I love him.

01:11:25.440 --> 01:11:28.480
John Brooke smiled, and his eyes were bright.

01:11:29.760 --> 01:11:35.840
Thank you, dearest Meg, he said. Do you love me? Will you marry me?

01:11:37.040 --> 01:11:39.520
Yes, I will, said Meg.

01:11:40.640 --> 01:11:48.240
Meg, said Aunt March. You are a very foolish girl. You will never get any money from me.

01:11:49.120 --> 01:11:53.360
Goodbye. She turned round and went quickly out of the room.

01:11:55.200 --> 01:11:58.320
Meg and John told the March family their good news.

01:11:59.440 --> 01:12:04.960
It's wonderful news, said Mr. and Mrs. March. Congratulations.

01:12:05.920 --> 01:12:09.280
Congratulations, said Amy and Beth together.

01:12:09.840 --> 01:12:15.040
Joe said nothing. She was not happy.

01:12:18.640 --> 01:12:25.520
Later, Lori and Mr. Lawrence came to the house. They congratulated Meg and John,

01:12:26.080 --> 01:12:28.480
but Lori looked at Joe's face.

01:12:29.360 --> 01:12:31.120
What's wrong, Joe?

01:12:31.600 --> 01:12:34.240
Asked Lori. Aren't you happy?

01:12:34.880 --> 01:12:36.320
No, said Joe.

01:12:36.320 --> 01:12:44.640
No, said Joe. Meg is my dear sister and my dear friend. Now John Brooke will take her away.

01:12:46.160 --> 01:12:53.840
Joe, said Lori. You love Meg. She is your sister. But John loves her too.

01:12:54.960 --> 01:13:00.480
Meg will be happy with John. And Joe, I'll always be your friend.

01:13:01.280 --> 01:13:05.040
That's true, said Joe. Thank you, Lori.

01:13:07.600 --> 01:13:11.360
Joe looked round the room. She looked at her family.

01:13:12.160 --> 01:13:18.400
Mr. and Mrs. March were talking together. Amy was sitting on the floor near Meg and John.

01:13:19.360 --> 01:13:21.760
Beth was talking to old Mr. Lawrence.

01:13:23.200 --> 01:13:27.520
Suddenly Joe was not sad anymore. She turned to Lori.

01:13:28.400 --> 01:13:31.280
You are right, Lori, she said.

01:13:32.400 --> 01:13:40.560
One day Meg will marry John, but she will always be my sister. We will always love each other.

01:13:41.600 --> 01:13:44.080
That's right, Joe, said Lori.

01:13:45.760 --> 01:13:50.880
Joe went over to Meg. She held Meg's hands and she kissed her face.

01:13:51.680 --> 01:13:58.480
Congratulations, dearest Meg, she said. I am very happy for you.

01:13:59.440 --> 01:14:06.640
And congratulations, John. You are our brother now. Welcome to our family.

01:14:06.640 --> 01:14:27.680
Little Women was read by Liza Ross, and the recording was produced by James Richardson at Studio AVP, London.

